To prove that the components of a Bernoulli random variable on a set $u$ are independent, we use the fact that its joint distribution is defined as a product measure (via `infinitePi`). Specifically, the distribution of $X$ is given by $Ber(u, p)$, which is the pushforward of an `infinitePi` measure under the map that converts a sequence of booleans into a set. Consequently, the joint distribution of the indicators $(i \in X(\omega))_i$ is exactly that `infinitePi` measure. Since a joint distribution being a product measure is equivalent to the independence of its components, the result follows.

We use `iIndepFun_iff_map_fun_eq_infinitePi_map` to relate the independence of the random variables to their joint distribution, and `measurePreserving_eval_infinitePi` to show that the product of the marginals matches the joint distribution.

```lean
lemma IsBernoulliOn.iIndepFun_mem (hX : IsBernoulliOn X u p P) :
    iIndepFun (fun i ω ↦ i ∈ X ω) P := by
  have hf : AEMeasurable (fun ω i ↦ i ∈ X ω) P :=
    MeasurableEquiv.setOf.measurable.comp_aemeasurable hX.aemeasurable
  refine (iIndepFun_iff_map_fun_eq_infinitePi_map hf).2 ?_
  rw [← hX.map_eq, bernoulliOn_eq_map, map_map MeasurableEquiv.setOf.measurable
    MeasurableEquiv.setOf.symm.measurable, MeasurableEquiv.self_comp_symm, map_id]
  simp [measurePreserving_eval_infinitePi]
```
